description.value: Fragment of an ostracon from a pottery vessel, showing remains of two(?) lines of hieratic in black ink written on the outside of the sherd. There are several black accretions at the outside which make it difficult to define the amount of lines of text.  The sherd is part of a plate with a diameter of about 25cm, very well finished at the inside, quite rough at the outside. Nile clay with chaff and mica inclusions, wheel turned, traces of clay scraped off at the outside. In the base of the vessel remains of black stains, possible used as a lamp.

description.value: Limestone ostracon with part of Kemit: four vertical lines of text in cursive hieroglyphs. The top edge is original, but the bottom edges are chipped.  The text is written in black between red ruled lines, and the metrical verses of the text are marked by horizontal red lines. The style of script and the layout of the text are characteristic of the composition entitled Kemit ('The Compendium'). The signs on this ostracon are rather clumsily written.
